'''''Epidermophyton floccosum''''' is an [[anthropophilic]] [[dermatophyte]] (preferring humans to other hosts) which can be found world-wide.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mycology.adelaide.edu.au/Fungal_Descriptions/Dermatophytes/Epidermophyton/ | title = Epidermophyton floccosum | accessdate = 2010-05-22 | work = Mycology Online}}</ref>

==Taxonomy==
The fungus was originally described by [[Carl Otto Harz]] in 1870, who named it ''Acrothecium floccosum''.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Harz OC. |year=1870 |title=Einige neue Hyphomyceten Berlin's and Wien's nebst Beiträgen zur Systematik derselben |journal= Bulletin de la Société Impériale des Naturalistes de Moscou |volume=44 |pages=87–147 |language=German }}</ref> It was later renamed ''Blastotrichum floccosum'', a name given to it in Rabenhort's ''Krytpogamen Flora'', (1907), and finally as ''Epidermophyton floccosum'' by Ota and Langeron in 1923.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ota M, Langeron M. |year=1923 |title=Nouvelle classification des Dermatophytes |journal=Annals of Parasitology |volume=1 |pages=305–306 |language=French}}</ref>

==Description==
The fungus is a moderate grower that reaches maturity after 10 days. The [[colony (biology)|colonies]] are usually grainy, have a [[suede]]-like texture, and may be olive, yellow, or yellow-brown in color. The central region is raised slightly. Fluffy white [[sterility (physiology)|sterile]] [[mycelium|mycelia]] cover the colonies after several weeks.<ref>{{cite journal | title = http://www.cmpt.ca/pdf_mycology_2008/mp_0801_2_epfl_nail.pdf | journal = CMPT Mycology Plus | date = January 2008}}</ref> ''Epidermophyton floccosum'' contains an unusual [[lipid]] of unknown function, 1(3),2-diacylglyceryl-3(1)-''O''-4′-(''N'',''N'',''N''-trimethyl)homoserine. Two other dermatophytes ''Microsporum cookei'' and ''[[Trichophyton rubrum]]'' do not contain this lipid.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0005-2760(79)90239-X | title = An unusual lipid in the human pathogenic fungus Epidermophyton floccosum | journal = Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (BBA) - Lipids and Lipid Metabolism | first1 = T | date = 1979-09-28 | last = Tomiyasu Yamada and Yoshinori Nozawa | volume = 574 | issue = 3 | pages = 433–439| id = | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6T1X-47G2PG4-60&_user=10&_coverDate=09%2F28%2F1979&_rdoc=1&_fmt=high&_orig=search&_sort=d&_docanchor=&view=c&_searchStrId=1344606088&_rerunOrigin=google&_acct=C000050221&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=10&md5=81a59da924fe1788a4843a5058f71f71 | accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> [[Microconidia]] are usually absent.<ref name=Nail />

==Pathology==
The fungus is the only pathogen of the two species comprising [[genus]] ''[[Epidermophyton]]''. [[Host (biology)|Hosts]] of the fungi are humans, wild animals, and domestic animals.<ref name=MSD>{{cite web | url = http://www.msdsonline.com/CustomerSupport/Disease-MSDS/MSDSEpidermophytonFloccosum.aspx | title = Infectious Diseases: ''Epidermophyton floccosum'', ''Microsporum'' spp., ''Trichophyton'' spp. | accessdate = 2010-05-22 | work = MSD Online}}</ref> The fungi can cause [[tinea pedis]], [[tinea cruris]], [[tinea corporis]], and [[onychomycosis]]. The infection spreads by contact, especially in gyms and showers.<ref name=Doctor_Fungus>{{cite web | url = http://www.doctorfungus.org/Thefungi/epidermophyton.htm | title = Epidermophyton spp. | accessdate = 2010-05-22 | work = Doctor Fungus}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The infection can be stopped by bathing with soap and water and applying an appropriate [[fungicide]].<ref name=MSD /> A study of 900 patients afflicted with ''E.&nbsp;floccosum'' infection investigating the contagious aspects of the fungus was conducted in [[Korea]], from 1976 to 1997. The study found that fewer people were infected by ''E.&nbsp;floccosum'' than by other dermatophytes.<ref>{{cite journal | title = The Epidemiologic Study on ''Epidermophyton floccosum'' (1976–1997) | journal = Korean Journal of Medical Mycology | date = 1999-06-04 | volume = 1 | issue = 21–26| id = | url = http://www.koreamed.org/SearchBasic.php?RID=656436&DT=1&QY=%22Korean+J+Med+Mycol%22+%5BJTI%5D++AND+1999+%5BDPY%5D+AND+Jun+%5BDPM%5Dd.org/SearchBasic.php?RID=656436&DT=1&QY=%22Korean+J+Med+Mycol%22+%5BJTI%5D++AND+1999+%5BDPY%5D+AND+Jun+%5BDPM%5D |accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> The fungus may be [[zoonosis|transmitted between]] humans and squirrels.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Hosseininejad | first1 = M. | last2 = Ebrahimi | first2 = A. | last3 = Hosseini | first3 = F. | title = Isolation of ''Epidermophyton floccosum'' from a Persian squirrel (''Sciurus anomalus'') | journal = Comparative Clinical Pathology | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 215–216 | year = 2009| doi = 10.1007/s00580-009-0829-4 | url = http://www.springerlink.com/content/8552251320242u22/ | accessdate = 2010-05-22}}</ref> The fungi can usually only infect the nonliving [[cornified layer]]s of [[Epidermis (zoology)|epidermis]].<ref name=Nail>{{cite web | url = http://qurnail.com/Epidermophyton.html | title = Epidermophyton | accessdate = 2010-05-22 | work = QurNail}}</ref> An invasive infection has, however, been recorded in an [[immunocompromised]] patient with [[Behçet's syndrome]].<ref name=Doctor_Fungus /><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Seddon | first1 = ME | last2 = Thomas | first2 = MG | title = Invasive disease due to Epidermophyton floccosum in an immunocompromised patient with Behçet's syndrome. | journal = Clinical Infectious Diseases | volume = 25 | issue = 1 | pages = 153–4 | year = 1997 | pmid = 9243051 | doi=10.1086/516887}}</ref>

